n` and `tb`). The golden testbench uses `clk`, `reset`, `ena` as inputs to `stimulus_gen`, and `hh_dut`, `mm_dut`, `ss_dut`, `pm_dut`, `tb_match` as inputs, while `wavedrom_title` and `wavedrom_enable` are outputs. The module name must be `TopModule` as specified in the input spec, but since the golden testbench uses `stimulus_gen` to instantiate the DUT, I must check which module the testbench is actually driving. The testbench instantiates `TopModule top_module1` and wires its outputs to DUT signals, but the stimulus generation logic is in `stimulus_gen`. Given the instruction to maintain the exact functionality and interface of the golden testbench, I will define the interface for the module being tested, which corresponds to `TopModule` in the testbench, but I must also account for the ports used in `stimulus_gen` if that\'s what\'s being tested. Since the prompt asks to test a module generated with the specification, and the specification describes `TopModule`, I will create the interface for `TopModule` based on the specification, but **the testbench structure heavily implies that the actual DUT being tested is the one whose signals are compared against `RefModule`**. The testbench instantiates `TopModule top_module1`. I will ensure the interface matches the ports used for `TopModule` in the testbench (which matches the input spec for `TopModule`). \\n\\n2. **Testbench Improvement:** The golden testbench needs significant modification to meet the new display requirements:\\n    * **Error Display:** The final `$display` must check `stats1.errors`. If 0, print \\"SIMULATION PASSED\\". Otherwise, print \\"SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\\".\\n    * **First Mismatch Display:** When `!tb_match` and `stats1.errors == 0` (i.e., the first error is detected), the state must be captured using dedicated registers (similar to the structure in the previous code, but fully implemented to capture all relevant signals: inputs to DUT, outputs from DUT, and expected outputs from RefModule).\\n    * **Signal Display Format:** For multi-bit signals ($\\text{width} \\text{<= } 64$), both HEX and BINARY must be displayed upon first mismatch. The helper task `display_first_mismatch` must implement this.\\n    * **Logic Maintenance:** All original functionality, including error counting logic and the structure of `stimulus_gen`, must be preserved.\\n\\n3. **Syntax Error Correction & Refinement:** The previous testbench showed numerous declaration errors (redeclaration of signals like `clk`, `reset`, etc.). This was likely due to copy/paste errors or attempting to reuse declarations across scopes. The final testbench must use distinct scope/declaration methods. I will fix the redundant declarations and ensure the capture logic is clean. The original comparison logic `(A !== (A ^ B ^ A))` simplifies to `(A !== B)`, so I will use explicit comparison `(ref !== dut)` for clarity in the error tracking, while maintaining the structure where possible, but crucially, I must implement the detailed state capture upon the first mismatch.\\n\\n4. **Implementation Details:** I will rename the signal capturing logic and ensure the new final block correctly handles the success/failure messages as requested. I will use the structure from the previous successful attempt but incorporate the specific required failure messages and signal formatting.",\n    "interface": "module TopModule (\\n    input logic clk,\\n    input logic reset,\\n    input logic ena,\\n    output logic pm,\\n    output logic [7:0] hh,\\n    output logic [7:0] mm,\\n    output logic [7:0] ss\\n);",\n    "testbench": "`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\\n`define OK 12\\n`define INCORRECT 13\\n\\n// =========================================================================\\n// Stimulus Generator Module (Copied from Golden Testbench structure)\\n// =========================================================================\\nmodule stimulus_gen (\\n\\tinput clk,\\n\\toutput reg reset,\\n\\toutput reg ena,\\n\\tinput [7:0] hh_dut, mm_dut, ss_dut,\\n\\tinput pm_dut,\\n\\tinput tb_match,\\n\\toutput reg[511:0] wavedrom_title,\\n\\toutput reg wavedrom_enable\\n);\\n\\ttask reset_test(input async=0);\\n\\t\\tbit arfail, srfail, datafail;\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t@(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\t@(posedge clk) reset <= 0;\\n\\t\\trepeat(3) @(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t@(negedge clk) begin datafail = !tb_match ; reset <= 1; end\\n\\t\\t@(posedge clk) arfail = !tb_match;\\n\\t\\t@(posedge clk) begin\\n\\t\\tsrfail = !tb_match;\\n\\t\\treset <= 0;\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\tif (srfail)\\n\\t\\ts\\n\\t\\tsdisplay(\\"Hint: Your reset doesn\'t seem to be working.\\");\\n\\t\\telse if (arfail && (async || !datafail))\\n\\t\\tsdisplay(\\"Hint: Your reset should be %0s, but doesn\'t appear to be.\\", async ? \\"asynchronous\\" : \\"synchronous\\");\\n\\t\\t// Don\'t warn about synchronous reset if the half-cycle before is already wrong. It\'s more likely\\n\\t\\t// a functionality error than the reset being implemented asynchronously.\\n\\tendtask\\n\\n\\t// Add two ports to module stimulus_gen:\\n\\t//    output [511:0] wavedrom_title\\n\\t//    output reg wavedrom_enable\\n\\n\\ttask wavedrom_start(input[511:0] title = \\"\\");\\n\\tendtask\\n\\t\\n\\ttask wavedrom_stop;\\n\\t\\th#1;\\n\\tendtask\\n\\t\\n\\t\\n\\tlogic bcd_fail = 0;\\n\\tlogic reset_fail = 0;\\n\\t\\n\\talways @(posedge clk) begin\\n\\t\\tif ((hh_dut[3:0] >= 4\'ha) ||\\n\\t\\t\\t(hh_dut[7:4] >= 4\'ha) ||\\n\\t\\t\\t(mm_dut[3:0] >= 4\'ha) ||\\n\\t\\t\\t(mm_dut[7:4] >= 4\'ha) ||\\n\\t\\t\\t(ss_dut[3:0] >= 4\'ha) ||\\n\\t\\t\\t(ss_dut[7:4] >= 4\'ha))\\n\\t\\t\\tbcd_fail <= 1\'b1;\\n\\tend\\n\\t\\n\\tinitial begin\\n\\t\\treset <= 1;\\n\\t\\tena <= 1;\\n\\t\\twavedrom_start(\\"Reset and count to 10\\");\\n\\t\\treset_test();\\n\\t\\trepeat(12) @(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\twavedrom_stop();\\n\\t\\tena <= 1\'b1;\\n\\t\\treset <= 1\'b1;\\n\\t\\t@(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\t@(posedge clk)\\n\\t\\tif (!tb_match) begin\\n\\t\\tsd